article.description: Rather than relying on Lindsay Whalen and Janel McCarville to do all the scoring, Minnesota found some balance Thursday night in a 78-46 win over Indiana.
article.headline: Andersson scores 17 points for Gophers
article.linkText: Minnesota clocks Indiana, snaps three-game skid
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Rather than relying on Lindsay Whalen and
Janel McCarville to do all the scoring, Minnesota found some
balance Thursday night in a 78-46 win over Indiana.

Kadidja Andersson scored 17 points to lead five players in
double figures as Minnesota (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) snapped a three-game losing
streak.

Minnesota (16-3, 5-3 Big Ten) beat the Hoosiers soundly after
consecutive losses to Purdue, Penn State and Michigan State -- all
ranked Big Ten opponents.

"We pretty much got shredded," Indiana coach Kathi Bennett
said. "We got outrebounded, outhustled -- you name it, we got
'out."

During the Gophers' skid, defenses keyed on Whalen, Minnesota's
leading scorer with 21.8 points per game. Whalen or McCarville had
led Minnesota in scoring the previous 14 games before Andersson
went 8-for-11 from the field Thursday.

"I've been trying to tell myself to shoot more," said
Andersson, whose season high is 18 points. "Since the Big Ten
started, teams are focusing more on Janel and Whalen, and we know
other people have to score."

McCarville scored 13, freshman Kelly Roysland had 12 points,
Whalen added 11 and Shannon Schonrock chipped in with 10 for
Minnesota, which had five players in double figures for the first
time this season.

"That's exactly what we wanted to do -- get more people involved
in the offense," Minnesota coach Pam Borton said. "We went
through a rough stretch last week and it was good to come back with
a good team effort."

The Gophers switched between zone and man-to-man frequently for
the first time this season and held the Hoosiers to 28 percent
shooting from the floor.

"Indiana is a team that loves to penetrate hard to the
basket," Borton said. "We knew we were going to switch it up
quite a bit, and I thought it really put them back on their
heels."

Bennett wasn't surprised by the zone, just frustrated with her
team's inability to shoot over it. "If anyone's got any tape on
us, they can see we pretty much struggle (against the zone)," she
said.

Cyndi Valentin scored 13 points, Leah Enterline added 11 and
Angela Hawkins scored 10 for the Hoosiers (10-9, 3-5).

After taking a 34-21 halftime lead, Minnesota opened the second
half with a 22-4 run over the first nine minutes. Andersson hit
three mid-range jumpers and Whalen -- who scored just four points in
the first half -- converted three of her patented layups in traffic
during that span.

"We've had a tendency to start slow in the second half and I
thought it was key for us to win the first four minutes of the
second half, to keep our tempo and intensity," Borton said.

The Gophers set the tone by outscoring the Hoosiers 14-2 over an
eight-minute span of the first half, surging to a 27-16 lead.
Roysland played a key role, scoring on a jump shot in the lane and
a fast-break layup on back-to-back possessions to force an Indiana
timeout.

Roysland played a season-high and team-high 31 minutes as she
expanded her role in the rotation. With Andersson shouldering the
scoring load, Whalen contributed in other areas, grabbing a
game-high nine rebounds.

"Having everybody on the court who can score makes us tough to
guard," Whalen said. "Kadidja was hot so we had to go to her. It
shows us that no one has to score 25 or 30 points for us to win a
game."
